Date: 0/0/1878
Source: Forty Years in NZ
Author: BULLER
Vol / Page: 295
Edition:
Quote: They took the name of Pikopo. This no doubt was maorified from the Latin word <i>episcopos</i>; but, unfortunately for them, it had the ominous meaning in the Maori tongue, - <i>creeping in the dark.</i>
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1930
Source: Fifty Years In Maoriland
Author: PINFOLD
Vol / Page: 99
Edition:
Quote: Even their name [sc Roman Catholics] may have hindered their progress. They were called Pikopo; the Maori attempt to reproduce the word <i>episcopos</i>. Unhappily for them, the word also means `creeping in the dark' : an idea which would not be helpful.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1936
Source: Treaty of Waitangi
Author: BUICK
Vol / Page: 118fn
Edition:
Quote: In his discussions with the Maoris, Bishop Pompallier had stresed the point that he held the advantage over the Protestant missionaries in that he was a member of the Episcopacy. The best attempt on the part of the natives to render into their own language the word Episcopos, in its varied forms, was <i>pikopo</i>, hence the Bishop and his converts became known as <i>Pikopo</i>.
Notes:
